Description : ΒΘ West is located at K/1,18–2/20,3/18. Excavation of this area continues the work first begun in 2008. \n\nThe record of this season's excavations was written digitally in the field, and supplemented by hundreds of digital photographs (2013.15.0001-0714). These photographs document the excavation of each basket, as well as all pottery recovered from each basket before it was processed and lotted. The field notes were then copied into paper notebooks (ΒΘ XVIII, pp. 3401-3600, ΒΘ XX, pp. 3801-3879), supplemented there by additional black and white photographs, cross-sections, and plans. A table of contents for the notebook, a catalog of coins and finds from this season, and an index have been included with the final report stored in the Stoa of Attalos. \n\nNomenclature for Byzantine rooms, walls, and architectural features will continue to be used in the same manner as in previous excavation seasons. See ΒΘ XVIII, p. 3422 for the beginning of season plan labeled with room numbers, wall numbers, excavation areas, and cross-sections.\n\nThe 2013 season will focus on six excavation areas within ΒΘ West: Rooms 2, 3, and 4 will continue to be excavated, and high fill around these rooms will be divided into the North Baulk, the Eastern Section, and the Southern Section. See the beginning of season plan for further clarification of this season's excavation areas, indicated in green, and digital photographs 2013.15.0003, .0005, .0007, and .0011.\n\nExcavation of the North Baulk continues work started in 2012, and is divided into Western and Eastern Sections. The Western Section (K/9,11-3/1,2) includes a small portion of the Animal Pit excavated mainly in 2009 and 2010. The Eastern Section (K/12,18-3/3,9) is composed of two primary areas (Area I to the west, Area II to the east), along with two control baulks (μάρτυρες) separating the primary areas and a baulk separating ΒΘ East and West.\n\nThe Eastern Section will focus on the removal of fills adjacent to the eastern boundary of ΒΘ West, which is defined by Modern Concrete Foundation (MCF) 5. The Eastern Section will be divided into a Northeastern Area (K/13,16-3/7,11) and Southeastern Area (K/11,13-3/9,15).\n\nThe Southern Section (K/1,11-3/10,18) will continue work from the 2011 field season.\n\nFieldwork began with a thorough cleaning of the trench, including the removal of a substantial collapse of fill from the northern scarp of the trench, which was the result of an unusually heavy rainfall in February 2013. The results of these activities, as well as all future cleaning operations and their out-of-context finds, are recorded in Basket 0.

Description : Open basket to investigate an area of high fill in the southwestern portion of the Southern Section. The excavation area is roughly rectangular in shape, measuring 3.35 m. east to west and 2.15 m. north to south, at its greatest extent.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact, with inclusions of stone, tile, glass, and bone. There is a concentration of tile and large stone in the northwestern corner of the excavation area, consisting primarily of broken roof and floor tiles, and stones roughly 10-15 centimeters in diameter.\n\nAfter the first pass, the tile and stone concentration remains localized to the northwestern corner of the excavation area, and we close to remove the tile and stone in a separate context (Basket 6).

The fill had been isolated in 2012 because of animal bones visible within the scarp, likely a continuation of the Animal Pit (see ΒΘ Lots 96-101, 129-130, 236-238, and 409).\n\nThe excavation area is rectangular in shape, measuring approximately 0.50 m. northeast to southwest, and 1.75 m. northwest to southeast. Description : Open basket to begin investigation of fill in the Northeastern Area of the Eastern Section. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring 3.35 m. northeast to southwest and 2.50 m. northwest to southeast, at its greatest extent.\n\nThe northwestern portion of the excavation area had been excavated in previous seasons (2012 Basket 109 and 2009 Basket 66), but approximately two thirds of the area (more specifically, the eastern and southern portions) is located directly below the spread footing of MCF 5, and was never excavated after the removal of the spread footings. During the 2009-2011 excavation seasons, the unexcavated area served as the location for the supervisor's desks.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of tile, bone and flakes of charcoal. As we remove fill, we expose more of the western face of MCF 5, which forms the eastern extent of the basket. Successive passes reveal no change in the composition of the fill, and we close arbitrarily.

Description : Open basket to investigate the tile and stone concentration in the northwestern corner of Southwestern Area. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 1.25 m. east to west and 1 m. north to south, at its greatest extend.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact, with inclusions of tile, stone, shell, bone, glass and glass slag, and charcoal.\n\nSuccessive passes indicate that the tile is located primarily in the western portion of the excavation area, while large stones are found in the east. We remove the tile, although some adhere to the concrete of Modern Wall 7 and cannot be removed. \n\nThe tiles consist of many broken roof cover and pan tile fragments, along with wall and floor tile fragments. We clean, sort, and photograph the tile fragments, before looking for joins. \n\nAfter removing the tiles, we leave the large stones in situ and close.

Description : Open basket to investigate fill in the Southeastern Area of the Eastern Section. The excavation area is roughly triangular in shape and measures 4.50 m. north to south and 2.25 m. east to west.\n\nThe grey-brown fill is moderately compact, with significant quantities of ash, and inclusions of pebbles, small stones, tile, bone and charcoal. \n\nDuring the first pass the excavators observe that in the western side of the excavation area, adjacent to Wall 13, the fill has no ash, and is light yellowish brown in color, rather than grey-brown. The proximity of this fill to Wall 13 suggests the possibility that it could be its foundation trench.\n\nIn the southern end of the excavation area, we reveal a concentration of medium sized stones, which could perhaps be the top of a wall.\n\nWe close basket after one pass, to excavate the area with the yellowish brown fill in a separate context (Basket 14).

Description : After taking the hypocaust tiles (ΒΘ 142 and ΒΘ 143) in Basket 9, we divide the high fill at the eastern end of Room 2 into northern and southern areas. Description : Open basket to investigate fill east of and adjacent to Wall 13. The excavation area is roughly rectangular, measuring ca. 2.00 m. north to south and 0.25 m. east to west.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact, with few inclusions of small stone and ceramic. We attempt to define a boundary between the light brown fill excavated within this basket and the greyish brown fill to the east, but the excavator does not find a distinct change. Successive passes indicate that the light brown fill extends further to the south and east, and is unlikely to be a foundation trench for Wall 13. We close to investigate the greyish-brown fill to the south and east.

Description : Open basket to continue investigation of fill in the Northeastern Area of the Eastern Section. The excavation area measures ca. 2.90 m. east to west and 4.50 m. north to south. \n\nThe greyish-brown fill is moderately compact and contains inclusions of charcoal, bone, tile, small to medium sized stones and glass and metal slag. As we take passes, we continue to expose the western face of MCF 5. We close arbitrarily and reopen the same excavation area in Basket 28.

Description : Open basket to continue investigation of the Southern Area. The excavation area measures ca. 0.90 m. east to west and 1.80 m. north to south.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of bone, glass, charcoal and plaster. As we take passes, we expose more of the cluster of stone in the center of the basket, which forms a rough line between the southern pier of Wall 16 and the western face of Wall 18. The excavator reveals a concentration of ash in the southeast corner of the basket, which is also visible in the disturbed fill below and to the south of the excavation area. \n\nWe divide the area into two regions, separated by the line of stone in the center of the basket, in order to investigate whether the stones are a purposefully built architectural feature. We close and reopen on Level 4a, the fill on the northern side of the cluster of stones, in Basket 30.

Description : Open basket to continue investigation of fill in Southeastern Area. After taking passes on the light brown fill east of and adjacent to Wall 13 in Basket 14, we now focus our efforts on the grey-brown fill to the south and east of Basket 14, which constitutes the majority of the Southeastern Area. The excavation area measures ca 4.60 m. north to south and 2.25 m. east to west at its greatest extent.\n\nThe grey-brown fill is moderately compact, with a significant amount of ash and charcoal flakes. Inclusions: stone, tile, bone, marble, metal, and metal slag.\n\nWe continue to define the western face of Modern Concrete Foundation (MCF) 5 as we descend, as well as more of the large classical block in the northeastern corner of the basket.\n\nThe excavator notes a significant concentration of tile, bone and plaster along the eastern boundary of the basket, which was cut by MCF 5. The plaster includes small pieces with a flat surface, which we leave in situ.\n\nIn the southern portion of the excavation area, we come down on more of the light brown fill, and also small pockets of sandy fill within the light brown. The small concentration of stone, which was revealed in Basket 7, does not continue. We remove it in this basket.\n\nWe close after one pass, with mixed fill (light brown to the west, grey-brown to the east) still characterizing the majority of the excavation area.

Description : Open basket to begin investigation of fill in Room 4, last excavated in Basket 96 of the 2012 season. We divide the room in half along its north-south axis, and open basket on the western half of the room.\n\nThe 2012 excavation season ended with the removal of the thick layer of loose rubbly fill that covered the entire room. The removal of this layer exposed the stone slab in the center of the room, and moderately packed fill around it, which had a gentle downward slope towards the stone slab in the center. See 2012 ΒΘ West End of Season Report, pg. 6, for more information on the 2012 stratigraphy in Room 4.\n\nThe excavation area is roughly rectangular in shape, measuring ca. 1.45 m. east to west by 2.80 m. north to south. It is bordered on the west by Wall 12, on the north and south by Walls 14 and 9, respectvely. The eastern portion of the excavation area cuts across the large marble block that lies in the center of Room 4, first exposed in Basket 80 of the 2012 season.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately packed with inclusions of bone and glass. The excavators find a bronze coin along the eastern face of Wall 12, which may be modern. While we wait for conservation to clean the coin, we close after one pass in order to minimize the potential repercussions.

Description : After removing the concentration of tile in Basket 6, we open to continue the removal of fill in the Southwestern Area. The area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 2.10 m. north to south and 2.85 m. east to west, at its greatest extent. We exclude the cluster of stone east of and adjacent to the tiles.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of small stone, tile, charcoal, metal slag, metal debris, glass, shell and bone.\n\nThe excavators reveal a concentration of dark ashy fill near the center of the excavation area, in which we find much metal debris and a carbonized seed. We photograph the ash patch and continue taking passes. Close arbitrarily, in preparation for the workmen to remove Modern Wall 7.

Description : Open basket to continue investigation of the western section of Room 4. The excavation area is roughly rectangular in shape, measuring 2.80 m. north to south and 1.45 m. east to west.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: small stone, tile, charcoal and glass slag. \n\nSuccessive passes reveal broken tile pieces below the stone slab in the center of the room, suggesting that the slab is covering a pithos built of reused tile. A plumb-bob dropped into a small opening at the side of the stone extends for approximately 2 meters before reaching solid ground.\n\nThe excavators reveal a glass rim and small sculpture fragment during successive passes. Close arbitrarily and reopen in Basket 32.

Description : Open basket to continue excavating the Northeastern Area of the Eastern Section. The basket is roughly triangular in shape, measuring 2.80 east to west by 4.40 m. north to south.\n\nThe grayish brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of charcoal, bone, plaster, tile, chunks of mudbrick and golf ball to grapefruit sized stones. As we take passes, we continue to expose the western face of MCF 5.\n\nSuccessive passes reveal stone in line with the southern trajectory of Wall 22, including a nicely preserved columnar grave monument. The excavators also note a soil change in the fill between Walls 18 and 22, from moderately compact grey-brown to loose and rubbly.\n\nImmediately to the south of the basket is a small and thin patch of concrete (ca. 0.60 x 0.55 m.) that spilled out into the fill to the west during the pouring of MCF 5. We remove the concrete and fill below out of basket, revealing more of the large classical block at the southern end of the excavation area, as well as other roughly faced stones that are likely a southern continuation of Wall 18.\n\nClose after several passes.

Description : Open basket to continue excavation of the Western Section of the North Baulk. The excavation area is roughly rectangular in shape, measuring 2.30 m. northwest to southeast by 0.60 m. northeast to southwest.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of plaster, charcoal and bone. The excavators note a higher concentration of bone and plaster in the northwestern portion of the excavation area, likely a part of the Animal Pit excavated in previous seasons. Upon noting this change in the composition of the fill, we close and reopen the portion of the excavation area that is part of the Animal Pit in Basket 31.

Description : Open basket on the northern side of the small cluster of stones revealed in Basket 19, in order to investigate whether the stones are a purposefully built architectureal feature. The basket is irregular in shape measuring ca. 1.05 m. northeast to southwest by 0.60 m. northwest to southeast.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact with much ash dispersed throughout the fill. Ash concentrations are particularly dense in the southeast portion of the excavation area, at the scarp below the cluster of stones that forms the southeastern extent of the basket, and in the northern area of the basket.\n\nAfter two passes, we pedestal the cluster of stones first exposed in Basket 19 and conclude that there are no courses of stone below those that we have already revealed. We close to take the fill south of the stone cluster (Level 4b) in Basket 34.

Description : Open basket on the portion of the Western Section with a higher concentration of bone and plaster. The excavation area is roughly rectangular in shape, measuring ca. 1.60 m. northwest to southeast by 0.40 m. northeast to southwest.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of charcoal flecks, plaster and bone. After one pass, the excavator comes down on articulated vertebrae and other bone fragments, also visible in the scarp. We close to take this concentration of bone in Basket 33.

Description : Open basket to continue the excavation of the Western Section of Room 4. The area is roughly rectangular, measuring ca. 2.80 m. north to south and 1.40 m. east to west, at its greatest extend.\n\nThe brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of charcoal, glass, tile and stone.\n\nThe excavators reveal a high concentration of stone and tile debris in the southern portion of the excavation area, north of and adjacent to Wall 9. Within this stone and tile debris is a well-preserved mudbrick, measuring 0.54 m. long and 0.11 m. wide. We photograph the stone and tile debris, and the mudbrick, and leave all in situ.\n\nAfter successive passes, we come down on patches of dark loose fill in the northwestern and southwestern corners of the excavation area. We close to investigate the loose fill in separate contexts.

Description : Open basket to continue investigation of the fill south of and adjacent to the stone cluster in the center of the Eastern Section of Room 2. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring 1.40 m. north to south by 0.95 m. east to west.\n\nThe moderately compact fill is light brown in color and ashy thoughout. Inclusions: bone, charcoal, ash, tile fragments, and patches of mudbrick. The excavator notes a higher concentration of ceramic sherds in Level 4b than in Level 4a to the north. The ash concentrations are particularly dense in two patches adjacent to the western face of Wall 18. We photograph and leave the ash patches in situ.\n\nAs we take passes, we pedestal the cluster of stones, conclude that they are not an architectural feature, and remove them. Close basket upon reaching the level of fill to the north.

Description : Open basket to continue excavation of the Southern Area. After investigating the fill north and south of the stone cluster in separate baskets and removing the stone cluster in Basket 34, Level 5 again encompasses the entire Southern Area.\n\nThe moderately compact fill is generally light brown in color. Inclusions: charcoal, ash, plaster flecks.\n\nIn the southwest portion of the excavation area, the fill is light brown to orange in color and includes a patch of mudbrick. In the eastern portion of the excavation area, adjacent to the western face of Wall 18, we take the two patches of ash left in situ at the close of Basket 34. The ash continues to the east, under the course of stones that may be the lowest course of Wall 18 (see digital photo 2013.15.0054).\n\nIn this same area, the excavator removes a medium-sized stone (ca. 15 cm. in length) and reveals a small empty space below part of Wall 18. Within the space more stone is visible, which may have been placed below Wall 18 as part of a leveling operation before the construction of the wall. The placement of the stones visible in the empty space is irregular and without coursing.\n\nSuccessive passes reveal more of the same light brown moderately compact fill, with flecks and small patches of ash and charcoal throughout. Close and reopen in Basket 44.

Description : Open basket to begin removal of fill in Area 1 of the North Baulk. The excavation area is irregular in shape measuring ca. 4.35 m. northwest to southeast by 1.15 m. northeast to southwest.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: ash, charcoal, flecks of plaster, bone, glass, metal and glass slag, tile, shell and small stones.\n\nAs we descend, we reveal more of the eastern face of Wall 18 at the western limit of the excavation area. In the center of the excavation area, against the northern scarp of trench ΒΘ, we come down on several roughly faced stones, two of which are intersecting at a right angle. The trajectory of one group of stones is parallel to Walls 18 and 22, but far enough east that it cannot be part of either of these walls. The elevation of these stones is roughly the same as the highest preserved course of Wall 18.\n\nClose arbitrarily.

Description : After isolating and removing part of the Animal Pit in Basket 33, we resume our excavation of the remaining fill in the Western Section of the North Baulk, last excavated in Basket 29. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 0.55 m. northeast to southwest by ca. 1.70 m. northwest to southeast.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of bone, charcoal, small chunks of plaster and flecks of ash. Bone and plaster are considerably less in this basket, perhaps suggesting that we have dug below the Animal Pit. After successive passes with no change in the composition of the fill, we close and reopen in Basket 50.

Description : Open basket to continue investigation of the Southern Area of the Eastern Section of Room 2. The excavation area is irregular in shape measuring ca. 1.65 m. north to south by ca. 1.00 m. east to west.\n\nThe moderately packed fill is light brown in color with ashy patches. After one pass, we come down on patches of very loose rubbly fill, one in the southern area of the excavation area and another in the northern. Successive passes confirm that we have reached the lowest course of Wall 18 in Basket 41, with ash layers extending beneath the wall at several points. (see digital photo 2013.15.0061).\n\nWe scrape away the moderately packed fill to expose more of the loose and rubbly. Close upon reaching the rubbly.

Description : Open basket to investigate the loose fill in the northwestern corner of Room 4. The excavation area is roughly circular and abuts Walls 12 and 14, measuring ca. 0.45 m. north to south and 0.40 m. east to west.\n\nThe fill is loose and grey-brown in color, with inclusions of bone and charcoal flecks. Successive passes reveal more of the light brown, moderately packed fill that surrounds the basket, gradually reducing the size of the excavation area into the shape of a small pit ca. 20 cm. in depth. The excavator finds a small roughly circular bronze disc, which may be a poorly preserved coin. We continue to scrape the loose grey-brown, until all that remains is moderately packed light brown fill. Close.

Description : Open basket to investigate the area of loose fill in the southwestern corner of Room 4. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 1.55 m. north to south and 0.50 m. east to west.\n\nAlthough the previous excavator noted softer fill in this area, the level of compaction does not turn out to be significantly different than the surrounding fill to the north and east. We take one pass and continue to find more of the stone and tile debris noted in Basket 32. Since there is no difference between this fill and that to the north and east, we close.

Description : Open basket to continue investigation of the Northeastern Area of the Eastern Section. The excavation area is roughly triangular in shape, measuring ca. 4.85 m. north to south and 2.80 m. east to west.\n\nThe light grey-brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of small stone, bone, tile, glass, glass slag, metal debris and metal slag.\n\nWe reveal more of Wall 22 as the pass proceeds, but do not find evidence for its southward continuation past Wall 9. A large roughly hewn stone suggests that Wall 9 continues to the east past Wall 18, intersecting with Wall 22.\n\nWe close in order to remove the loose rubbly fill between Walls 18 and 22 in Basket 53.

Description : Open basket to continue the removal of fill in the western section of Room 4. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 2.65 m. north to south and 1.50 m. east to west, at its greatest extent.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: small to fist-size stone, tile, charcoal flecks, plaster, bone and glass. Successive passes reveal more of the tile lining of the pithos. We leave the stone and tile debris in the southern portion of the excavation area in situ, and do not find evidence for its continuation or expansion in this basket.\n\nClose and reopen arbitrarily in Basket 64.

Description : After taking the moderately compact fill from the Southern Area of the Eastern Section of Room 2 in Basket 44, we open on the rubbly fill underneath. The excavation area is irregular in shape measuring ca. 1.50 m. north to south by ca. 0.80 m. east to west.\n\nThe rubbly fill is loose and pebbly throughout. Inclusions: ash, bone and charcoal. A high concentration of ash is present in the northern portion of the excavation area and contains inclusions of bronze, chunks of charcoal and iron slag. Successive passes continue to reveal courses of Walls 14 and 16 as we descend.\n\nIn the southeastern corner of the basket, at the intersection of Walls 18 and 14, we find a disturbance of modern concrete mixing with the lowest courses of Wall 18. It is likely part of the spread footing from Modern Concrete Foundation 6, and it appears that several of the stones adjacent to this wall are part of this modern concrete disturbance. We chip away at the concrete, but leave much in situ, lest we lose parts of Wall 18 while removing the concrete disturbance.\n\nWe close upon reaching the approximate level of the same rubbly fill in the rest of Room 2 to the west.

Description : Open basket to continue removal of fill from the Western Section of the North Baulk. The excavation area is irregular in shape measuring ca. 2.30 m. northwest to southeast by ca. 0.60 m. northeast to southwest.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: bone, charcoal, ash\n\nAs we take passes, we come down on a pile of rubble in the eastern half of the excavation area composed of tiles and small sized stones. We remove the rubble in passes. We close arbitrarily and reopen in Basket 56.

Description : Open basket to continue removal of fill in the Southeastern Area, most recently excavated in Basket 20. We limit the excavation area to areas of higher fill in the south, which had been left at the close of Basket 20. The excavation area is roughly triangular in shape, measuring ca. 2.55 m. north to south and 0.85 east to west. We exclude the roughly circular area of sandy fill and the plaster and charcoal concentration found during Basket 20. \n\nThe moderately compact fill is mostly light brown in color with patches of ashy grey-brown. Inclusions: charcoal, bone and metal. The excavator finds a nail near the eastern face of Wall 13, which may be modern. We save the nail for lotting.\n\nAfter taking a pass on the moderately compact light brown, we expand to the east to investigate the plaster and charcoal concentration. We find more pottery than in the light brown fill, as well as metal debris, charcoal and painted plaster with a flat surface. We close to excavate this area and the sandy fill in separate contexts (Baskets 60 and 58, respectively).

Description : Open basket to continue removal of fill from Area 1 of the Eastern Section of the North Baulk. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 4.30 m. northwest to southeast by ca. 1.30 m. southwest to northeast at its greatest extent. The light brown fill is moderately compact, with inclusions of charcoal, ash, tile, shell, bone and glass. \n\nAs we take passes, we continue to expose more of the group of stones first revealed in Basket 42. We reveal two courses on one face of a roughly square feature, which follows the north-south alignment of Walls 18 and 22. Although one side of this square feature (facing west) is roughly faced with worked stone, a second side (facing south) is less regular, so far composed of unfaced stone, along with broken tile and smaller stone. The northern extent of the square feature is concealed by the northern scarp of the trench.\n\nTo the north of the roughly faced course of stones, a large square stone abuts this square feature at a right angle. A rough line of unfaced stones proceeds to the southwest from this square stone, not yet reaching Wall 18.\n\nAfter successive passes we bring the fill down to the level of fill immediately to the southwest, which was directly below the course of Wall A. This fill had only been excavated in one basket since the removal of Wall A in 2008 (see 2008 Basket 50 and 2011 Basket 50).\n\nWe close and reopen in Basket 54, expanding the excavation area to include the fill below Wall A to the south.

Description : Open basket to remove a small area of loose fill between Walls 18 and 22, first revealed during Basket 28. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 0.45 m. northeast to southwest by ca. 1 m. northwest to southeast at its greatest extent.\n\nThe moderately packed fill is light brown in color. Inclusions: metal debris, tile fragments, pebbles, small stones and glass slag. \n\nThe excavator notes that pockets of moderately packed fill persist within the loose rubbly. Although this fill was looser than the moderately packed fill above, the soil change between these two fills is gradual and uneven in elevation, and we are likely digging a layer of mixed fill- the moderately packed light brown above, and the loose, grainy, rubbly fill below.\n\nWe close after two passes, as the fill becomes uniformly grainy and rubbly.

Description : Open basket to continue investigation of Area 1. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 3.75 m. southeast to northwest by ca. 1.75 m. southwest to northeast at its greatest extent.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of metal slag, glass, tile, plaster, flecks of charcoal and ash, and bone.\n\nSuccessive passes continue to reveal more of the stone features discussed in Baskets 42 and 52. Cleaning operations in the southeastern corner of the excavation area reveal that the intrusion of modern concrete found on the west and south of Wall 18 (see Basket 49) is also present on the east side of the wall. The excavator reveals a small hole in the vicinity of the concrete intrusion, extending northward into Basket 54's excavation area. Due to the likelihood of a collapse of fill into the hole within the next few passes, we close and reopen over the approximate area of the hole in Basket 67.

Description : With Modern Wall 7 removed over the long weekend, we open basket to remove the remains of the tile concentration that were beneath Wall 7. See Basket 6 for excavation of the majority of the tile concentration, to the west.\n\nThe excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 0.35 m. north to south and 0.60 m. east to west. The light brown fill is moderately compact with much tile, bone, plaster and flecks of charcoal.\n\nThe tiles consist of roof, wall and floor tile fragments, some of which bear finger impressions. We clean, sort, and photograph the tile fragments. With the tiles removed, we close.

Description : Open basket to continue excavation of the Western Section of the North Baulk. The excavation area is roughly rectangular in shape measuring ca. 2.50 m. northwest to southeast by ca. 0.75 m. northeast to southwest.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: bone, tile, small stones. Successive passes reveal more of the northern face of Wall 11, and a series of stones that suggest a northern continuation of Wall 16. The excavators also expose a piece of worked stone (part of a small column?) at the northern scarp, close to the northern face of Wall 11. We close upon reaching the level of fill to the south.

Description : Open basket to begin removal of fill exposed by the demolition of Modern Wall 7. The excavation area is roughly rectangular in shape, measuring ca. 0.70 m. north to south and 2.85 m. east to west, at its greatest extent.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of charcoal, plaster, metal slag, bone and shell. We close arbitrarily after one pass in order to focus our excavation efforts elsewhere.

Description : Open basket to investigate the fill of plaster and ash in the middle of the eastern side of the Southeastern Area in the Eastern Section. The area is roughly triangular in shape, measuring ca. 1.25 m. north to south and 1.10 m. east to west.\n\nThe fill varies from light to greyish-brown color and is moderately compact with inclusions of plaster, stone, charcoal, tile and mudbrick. We find significant quantities of painted plaster with a flat surface, which we save for lotting.\n\nAfter several passes we come down on fill similar in character to the surrounding area, and we begin to find less plaster and ash. With the high concentrations of plaster and ash removed, we close.

Description : Open basket to begin investigation of the Northern Area in the Eastern Section of Room 2. \n\nThe Northern Area is partly below the course of Wall A, and partly below fill removed during the excavation of the North Baulk in 2012. See 2011 Basket 82 for the excavation of fill below Wall A, and 2012 Basket 115 for the lowest level of fill removed during the excavation of the North Baulk.\n\nThe Basket 62 excavation area measures ca. 0.70 m. northwest to southeast by ca. 0.40 m. northeast to southwest, and is restricted to a high concentration of tile debris that is visible in the southern scarp of the Northern Area.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of bone, flecks of charcoal, and ash. We take the tile debris in two passes, exposing more of the northern pier of Wall 16 in the process. Upon reaching the light brown moderately packed fill beneath, we close.

Description : Open basket to continue investigaton of fill in the Western Section of Room 4. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 2.60 m. north to south and 1.45 m. east to west, at its greatest extent.\n\nThe fill is light brown in color and moderately compact. Inclusions: bone, tile, small to medium-sized stone (especially in the northern side of the basket) and glass. A sculpture fragment (ΒΘ 163) is also found in the fill of this basket, very close to the findspot of another sculpture fragment (ΒΘ 156). Both are likely part of a Herm.\n\nWe come down on patches of loose fill in the area adjacent to the perimeter of the pithos, which could be building fill from construction of the pithos. We close in order to investigate the looser fill in a separate context.

Description : After removing the rubble debris from the Northern Area of the Eastern Section of Room 2 in Basket 62, we open on the remaining high fill between Walls 11 and 18. The excavation area is irregular in size measuring ca. 1.60 m. northwest to southeast by ca. 0.95 m. northeast to southwest.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: bone, flecks of ash and small chunks of plaster. As we take passes, we continue to reveal courses of Walls 11 and 18. After successive passes, the fill against Walls 11 and 18 remains moderately compact while the fill in the southern part of the excavation area becomes sllightly looser with a high concentration of ash and pebbles. We close and reopen in Basket 68.

Description : After investigating the sandy fill and the fill with plaster and ash in separate baskets (see Baskets 58 and 60), we open on the entire Southeastern Area. The basket is roughly triangular in shape, measuring ca. 4.50 m. north to south and 2.05 m. east to west.\n\nThe fill is moderately compact, with color varying from light brown to grey-brown. Inclusions: stone, tile, bone, glass slag, and a considerable charcoal concentration in the southern side of the basket.\n\nThe excavator reveals patches of loose rubbly fill on the western side of the excavation area, adjacent to the eastern face of Wall 13. Two patches of this loose fill widen slightly with successive passes, but the majority of the fill in the excavation area remains moderately compact. Close and reopen in Basket 78, excluding the loose rubbly fill.

Description : Open basket to investigate fill surrounding a hole associated with a modern concrete intrusion in the vicinity of Wall 18. Cleaning around the concrete indicates that it continues northward below the fill in Area 1.\n\nThe excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 0.70 m. north to south by ca. 0.85 m. east to west.\n\nAround the hole, the light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: small plaster chunks, ash, charcoal. In the southern part of the excavation area, immediately above and around the concrete, we find modern plastic debris. A small coin (ΒΘ-217) was found during out of basket cleaning in this same area, shortly before we opened the basket. \n\nWe expose a smoothly faced stone at the western edge of the basket, which runs perpendicular to the stone feature north of the basket.\n\nWith successive passes we expose more of the hole and concrete, which expands out into a large open area, approximately 55 cm. below the current level of the surrounding fill. The open cavity continues under Wall 18 to the west.\n\nAfter exposing all of the concrete intrusion, clearing the fill around it, and determining the full extent of the cavity, we close.

Description : Open basket to investigate the loose fill surrounding the pithos, which could potentially be associated with the structure's construction. The excavation area is roughly semicircular in shape, measuring ca. 1.90 m. north to south and 0.35 m. east to west.\n\nThe light brown fill has inclusions of bone, tile, stone and flecks of charcoal. The excavator reports that the loose fill is confined to a small area near the center of the excavation area, and elsewhere there is no significant difference between the fill next to the pithos and the rest of the fill in the Western Section. \n\nFill in this basket continues to have a high quantity of tile debris, but we have found many similar concentrations throughout the investigation of the Western Section of Room 4 over the course of the season, and the presence of high quantities of tile debris does not represent a significant difference from fill in the rest of the room.\n\nUpon determining that there is no significant difference in compaction, color, or content of the fill surrounding the pithos and that in the rest of the Western Section, we close.

Description : Open basket to investigate the small triangular area of fill surrounded by Walls 8, 9 and 13, most recently excavated in 2012 Basket 85. The excavation area measures ca. 2.05 m. north to south and 0.75 m. east to west.\n\nThe brown fill is loose and rubbly, similar in consistency to the fills found in Rooms 1 and 4, and below the Tile Surface South of Wall 9 (See ΒΘ Lots 389, 415, and 425). Inclusions: tile, bone, glass.\n\nAfter successive passes, we come down on moderately compact light brown fill. We reveal more courses of Wall 13, but below Walls 8 and 9 we find fill with few stones, unlikely to be part of lower courses of the walls. The portions of Walls 8 and 9 adjacent to this excavation area are composed of small unfaced stone, unlike the handsomely faced stone of Wall 13. See 2012 Basket 85 and pp. 5-6 of the 2012 end of season report for more discussion of these walls.\n\nWith the loose rubbly fill removed, we close.

DateUTC : [2013-07-17T04:28:26Z TO 2013-07-22T09:45:08Z]
Deposit : K 3:2
Description : With excavation of the Western Section of the North Baulk concluded in Basket 63, we are now prepared to investigate the remaining high fill comprising the northwestern corner of Room 3. This high fill extends from Wall 21 at the west to Wall 16 at the east, measuring ca. 3.90 m. The northern scarp of the trench defines the northern boundary of the excavation area (ca. 1 m. of high fill between the portion of Room 3 excavated in 2012 and the northern scarp of the trench).\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: glass slag, metal debris, tile, bone. As we take passes, we continue to expose the face Wall 16 at the eastern edge of the basket. \n\nAt the west, we investigate the concentration of stone in the vicinity of Wall 21. The northern face of Wall 21 is well defined and continues westward past Wall 12, but the southern face of this wall is mostly obscured by a large scatter of stone and tile debris. Investigation of this debris reveals a second southern face, indicating that either Wall 21 is approximately 1.20 m. wide, has more than one phase, or that there are two walls on the north side of Room 3.\n\nSuccessive passes indicate that we are well below the fragmentary door sill, which is clearly not in its original context. We remove the sill, which has indentations for doors on both sides. Below the sill, we come down on part of a large coarseware vessel. The excavator also finds many joining fragments of a bowl with poorly preserved glaze. The presence of these vessels suggests that we are finding a continuation of Deposit K 3:2.\n\nWe close to take the fill within the large coarseware vessel in a separate context.

Description : After investigating and defining the modern concrete intrusion in the vicinity of Wall 18 and the open cavity to the north of the concrete (see Basket 67), we resume excavation of Area 1 in Basket 73. The excavation area is confined to fill east of the cavity, measuring ca. 1.70 m. northeast to southwest by ca. 2.20 m. northwest to southeast.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: metal debris, charcoal, small chunks of plaster, glass, bone, tile. As we take passes, we continue to expose and detail the stone features discussed in Baskets 42 and 52. We find further courses of stone facing northwest, but the southern and eastern boundaries of the stone feature remain unclear. It seems likely that the eastern edge of the feature is obscured by a pile of rubble debris.\n\nAfter successive passes and no change in the composition of the fill, we close and reopen in Basket 80.

Description : Upon confirming that the stone and tile debris in the southern portion of the Western Section is pedestaled, we open basket to remove the debris. The excavation area is roughly rectangular in shape, measuring ca. 1.45 m. east to west and 0.55 m. north to south.\n\nWe remove the stone and tile debris in successive passes, and come down on the same light brown, moderately compact fill that has characterized excavation in the majority of the Western Section of Room 4. Among the tiles there is a large fragment of a drain tile, as well as roof, floor and wall tile fragments.\n\nThe excavator removes all of the debris and we close once the basket has been brought to the level of the surrounding fill.

Description : Open basket to continue investigation of fill in the Northern Area of the Eastern Section of Room 2. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 1.65 m. northwest to southeast by ca. 1.45 m. northeast to southwest.\n\nThe moderately packed fill is dark brown in color. Inclusions: small stones, pebbles, tile, charcoal, ash, plaster, bone, metal slag. As we take passes, we continue to expose patches of rubbly fill throughout the excavation area, with inclusions of pebbles, small stones and tile fragments. The moderately compact fill persists in the northeastern corner of the basket, and we continue to scrape it away until we come down on the rubbly. The northeastern corner is therefore approximately 10-15 cm. lower than the rest of the excavation area.\n\nWe close to take the rubbly fill in Basket 77.

Description : Open basket to continue removal of fill in the Western Section of Room 4, after excavating fill around the pithos in Basket 69. The excavation area is roughly rectangular in shape, measuring ca. 2.80 m. north to south and 1.35 m. east to west.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact, similar to previous baskets in the area. Inclusions: bone, glass, tile. The northern part continues to show a cosiderable concentration of scattered stones. \n\nAfter the first pass we expand the basket to include the semicirular area around the pithos, since there is no difference in fill between the two areas. Close after the second pass.

Description : Open basket to remove the rubbly fill in the Northern Area of the Eastern Section of Room 2. The excavation area is roughly triangular in shape, measuring ca. 1.60 m. northwest to southeast by ca. 1 m. northeast to southwest. As noted in Basket 75, the northeastern corner is approximately 10-15 cm. lower in elevation than the rest of the excavation area.\n\nThe rubbly fill is loose and sandy and dark brown in color. Inclusions: metal slag, bone, small fragments of tile, small stones and pebbles. As we take passes, we come down on moderately packed fill in the northern part of the basket. When we come down to the level of the surrounding rubbly fill in Room 2, we close.

Description : Open basket to continue removal of fill in the Southeastern Area. The excavation area is roughly triangular in shape measuring ca. 4.60 m. north to south and 2.00 m. east to west. We exclude two small patches of loose rubbly fill along the eastern face of Wall 13, which were exposed in Basket 66.\n\nThe fill has the same color variation from grey-brown to light brown, as noted in the previous baskets of the area. Inclusions: tile, bone, metal and glass slag, bronze debris and charcoal flecks.\n\nSuccessive passes reveal a bit more of the rubbly fill but the majority of the area is still moderately compact. Close.

Description : Open basket to investgate fill between the architectural feature in Area 1 and Wall 18. The excavation area is roughly rectangular in shape, measuring ca 1.00 m. north to south by ca. 0.15 m. east to west. A large, smoothly faced stone is visible in the scarp below the excavation area, which was revealed during investigation of the open cavity in Basket 67.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: bone and small tile fragments. Successive passes expose the top of the smoothly faced stone visible in the scarp, which is rectangular and appears to continue under Wall 18 to the west. A large stone from the architectural feature in Area 1 also lies on top of the same stone.\n\nWith the relationship between the rectangular, roughly faced stone, Wall 18, and the architectural feature in Area 1 defined, we close.

Description : Open basket to continue removal of fill around the architectural feature in Area 1. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 2.15 m. northwest to southeast by ca. 1.70 m. northeast to southwest at its greatest extent.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: small chunks of plaster, charcoal, ash, bone, metal slag, glass slag and glass. \n\nAs we take passes, we continue to expose courses of the western face of Wall 24, which defines the eastern side of the architectural feature. The wall is composed of roughly faced stone and tile spolia with joints of fill.\n\nIn the southern part of the basket, \nwe come down on a line of stone that may define the southern boundary of the architectural feature. Their alignment is perpendicular to Walls 18, 22 and 24, but at present the shape and composition does not prove that it is more than a small concentration of stone and tile that happens to be in the correct position to suggest a southern boundary of a square architectural feature.\n\nSuccessive passes also reveal more of the northern side of the feature, and the fill begins to fall away in the northeastern corner of the feature, perhaps suggesting a continuation of the cavity to the east.\n\nWe close after several passes, with the level of fill the same as that in Area 2 to the east.

Deposit : K 3:2
Description : We open basket in Room 3 to take the fill within the coarseware vessel (later determined to be a pithos) exposed in Basket 71. The excavation area is roughly circular in shape with a diameter of 0.60 m.\n\nIn consultation with the excavation's Byzantine pottery specialist, Dr. Joanita Vroom, we save the fill within the pithos in several levels, recording the starting elevation of each level and photographing our progress as we descend in 3 cm. passes. In Level 0, we save the fill from against the southeastern face of Wall 23. All fill from the first two levels within the pithos is saved in Levels 1 and 2.\n\nAs we descend, Dr. Vroom determines that the vessel is a pithos. For this reason, she advises that we save only ca. 3 cm. of fill adjacent to the vessel wall in Levels 3, 4 and 5. In Levels 6 and 7, when the bottom of the pithos begins to be visible, we save all fill. Upon the removal of Level 7, the bottom of the pithos is fully exposed.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: bone, charcoal, shell, small chunks of plaster and tile and apricot to grapefruit sized stones (ca. 10 cm. in diameter). The excavator notes several tile fragments and four medium sized stones (ca. 10 cm. by 10 cm.) in the fill of Levels 3-4. Levels 6 and 7 comprise fill with few inclusions.\n\nAfter we take Level 7, we close to excavate the fill around the pithos in a separate context.

DateUTC : [2013-07-23T04:48:14Z TO 2013-07-25T10:17:39Z]
Description : Open basket to investigate fill in in the large, central section of Room 2, previously excavated in 2012 Basket 67. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 2.95 m. north to south by 2.30 m. east to west.\n\nWe start with a deep cleaning pass over the entire Central Section of Room 2. Moderately packed light brown fill covers the majority of the Central Section, with loose rubbly fill around the western and northern edges. We open on the moderately packed fill in the center, extending south to the northern face of Wall 14 and the western face of the southern pier of Wall 16.\n\nThe brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of bone, metal slag, bronze debris, plaster and charcoal. \n\nSuccessive passes reveal some patches of loose rubbly fill in the southwestern corner of the basket, but the majority of the area consists of moderately compact to slightly looser fill. We close after two passes, arbitrarily.

Description : Open basket on high fill in the Western Section of Room 2. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 0.80 m. north to south by ca. 0.30 m. east to west.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of bone and small chunks of charcoal. As we take passes, we extend the basket in all directions, taking the moderately compact fill which has patches of ash in the eastern part of the Western Section. When we come down to the level of fill to the south, we close.

Deposit : K 3:2
Description : After excavating the fill within the pithos in Basket 81, we open on the surrounding fill south of Wall 23, dividing the high fill in Room 3 arbitrarily. The basket is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 1.90 m. east to west by ca. 1.15 m. north to south.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: bone, glass, plaster, metal slag and glass slag.\n\nAs we take passes, we find a coin (ΒΘ-220) and expose fragments of several roof cover and pan tiles on the eastern side of the pithos. We close arbitrarily and reopen in Basket 96.

DateUTC : [2013-07-25T06:37:16Z TO 2013-07-30T05:48:29Z]
Description : Open basket to remove the large area of loose rubbly fill that covers much of the eastern portion of the Southern Section. Due to heavy foot traffic and lack of excavation in previous seasons, the fill is removed in one large pass over the entire eastern half of the Southern Section, in an effort to begin future work in the area on firmer ground. The excavation area measures ca. 4.90 m. north to south by 3.05 m. east to west.\n\nThe brown fill is very loose and grainy, with inclusions of bone, shells, tile, stone, plaster and glass. Its consistency and inclusions are similar to the rubbly fills found in Rooms 1 and 4, and below the Tile Surface South of Wall 9, during the 2012 season (see ΒΘ Lots 389, 415, and 425). \n\nBelow the loose rubbly we find a moderately compact light brown fill. In the center of the excavation area, however, the loose rubbly continues deeper, forming a distinctive circular pit, which we leave in situ. \n\nWe extend the excavation area to the south, taking more loose rubbly until we reach the southern scarp of Trench ΒΘ. The excavators reveal a large area of moderately compact light brown fill, similar in appearance to large slabs of mudbrick. We leave this fill in situ.\n\nAt the north, close to the southern face of Wall 9, the loose rubbly fill continues further down into a small trench that was dug parallel to the wall- perhaps an unlined drainage channel?\n\nWith the loose rubbly fill removed, we close.
Identifier : 88

Description : Open basket on the stone and tile debris left in situ after Basket 42, between the architectural feature, Wall 24, and the northern scarp of ΒΘ West. Based on the alignment of the larger stones, it seems likely that there is an eastern face to Wall 24, with the stone and tile debris against it. The basket is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 0.50 m. northwest to southeast by ca. 0.35 m. northeast to southwest.\n\nWe take the tile and stone debris in passes, gradually exposing the larger stones. The light brown fill is moderately compact with a high concentration of fist-sized stones and tile fragments. We find that the larger stones do not have worked facing, however, and there appears to be no clearly defined eastern side of Wall 24.\n\nSince the stone and tile debris may in fact be part of the architectural feature (backfill behind the larger stones?), we close after two small passes and leave the majority of the debris in situ.

Description : Open basket to remove a small area of loose pebbly fill east of and adjacent to Wall 93. The excavation area measures ca. 2.05 m. north to south by 0.40 m. east to west.\n\nThe grey-brown fill is loose and sandy with inclusions of stone, bone, metal slag, charcoal and bronze debris. After one pass we come down on more compact fill, which generally characterizes the rest of the Southeastern Area, and close.

Description : Open basket to continue investigation of fill in the Northeastern Area. We limit the excavation area to the fill adjacent to the intersection of Walls 9 and 22, which at present is defined only by a few stones. The basket is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 3 m. north to south and ca. 1.60 m. east to west, at its greatest extent.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: bone, metal slag and small chunks of plaster. We find one additional stone at the intersection of the walls, but their juncture remains scrappy. We also find a concentration of stone and tile debris near the eastern face of Wall 18, which may be related to the larger cluster of stone and tile on the opposite side of the same wall. We close after two passes, in order to bring the fill to the northeast down to the same level before the end of the excavation season.

Deposit : K 3:2
Description : Open basket to continue investigation of fill surrounding the pithos in Room 3. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 1.90 east to west by ca. 1 m. north to south.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact. Inclusions: bone, tile, glass slag and glass. As we take passes, we find four coins (BΘ-221, ΒΘ-225, ΒΘ-226, and ΒΘ-227) in the vicinity of the south face of Wall 23, east of the pithos. We continue to expose and remove several roof cover and pan tile fragments in the center of the excavation area.\n\nAfter two passes, we come down on a yellowish-brown surface feature east of the pithos. The level of the surface slopes downward to the east, and continues west under the pithos, indicating that the pithos rests on it. With the fill surrounding the pithos removed, we close and reopen in Basket 100 to continue investigating the surface feature and to remove the pithos.

Description : Open basket to remove the loose rubbly fill along the western and northern edges of the Central Section of Room 2. The excavation area is Γ-shaped, measuring ca. 2.95 m. north to south by ca. 2.80 m. east to west.\n\nThe grey-brown fill is loose and rubbly. Inclusions: small stones, tile fragments, bone, glass and metal slag.\n\nIn the northwest corner of the basket, we quickly come down on \nmoderately compact fill, similar in consistency to the fill removed in Basket 92. The loose rubbly continues, however, in the east and south, and we take passes until we reach the level of the fill in the middle of the Central Section. We close to take the moderately compact fill in Basket 101.

Description : With the Southeastern Area now at roughly the same elevation as the fill to the north, we open basket to investigate this northern fill, which was previously dug in 2012 Basket 106. The excavation area is roughly rectangular, measuring ca. 1.55 m. north to south by 2.05 m. east to west.\n\nThe fill is moderately compact with a considerable quantity of scattered rocks and tile and has a color variation from light brown in the eastern part to gray-brown in the western. Inclusions: bone.\n\nIn the northeastern corner of the basket we find a significant concentration of stone and tile, which we leave in situ. We close after two additional passes over the lower fill, due to end of season.

The excavation area is roughly triangular, measuring ca. 1.15 m. northwest to southeast by 0.40 m. southwest to northeast.\n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact with very few inclusions-bone, glass, and small pieces of wood (possibly related to a nearby root?). \n\nWe close after bringing the basket down to the level of the surrounding fill.

Deposit : K 3:2
Description : After exposing part of the yellowish-brown surface feature in the fill south of and adjacent to Wall 23, we open to continue investigating the extent of the feature to the east. The boundaries of the excavation area remain the same as Baskets 86 and 96.\n\nSuccessive passes continue to reveal more of the surface feature. We find bits of charcoal on and embedded within the surface, along with stone and tile debris. The northern boundary of the surface is less uniform and definite than the boundary in the west, with an undulating border tapering off into the surrounding gray fill. The surface continues sloping downward to the eastern boundary of the excavation area. After defining the limits of the feature at the north and east, we remove the pithos and define the western boundary, which does not connect with Wall 23. The southern boundary is also not clearly defined. At several points it is close to the southern scarp, but there is no clear evidence that it continued southward into the portion of Room 3 excavated in 2012.\n\nNorth of the surface feature, we scrape away at the moderately compact grey-brown fill and reveal  a glazed bowl, with large pieces of burnt wood in the vicinity. We also find four more coins during our investigation of fill above and around the surface, bringing the total number of coins found in Baskets 86, 96 and 100 to nine. We have also saved all tile fragments found during excavation of these baskets, and we recover an almost complete roof cover tile (ΒΘ 180) after washing and sorting the tiles.\n\nWith the pithos removed and the surface defined, we close due to end of season.

Description : Open basket to continue removal of fill in the Southeastern Area. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 4.60 m. north to south by 2.00 m. east to west.\n\nThe fill is moderately compact, and light brown in color. Inclusions: tile, glass, plaster, metal and glass slag, charcoal and bronze debris.\n\nAfter two deep passes we bring the basket down to the level of fill to the north, and close due to end of season.

Description : Open basket to remove high fill left as a baulk between the Western and Central Sections of Room 2. The excavation area is roughly rectangular, measuring ca. 2.25 m. north to south by 0.70 m. east to west.\n\nThe grey-brown fill is generally loose with the exception of the northern and southern edges of the excavation area, where the excavators come down on moderately compact yellowish-brown (decomposing mudbrick?). We photograph the yellowish-brown and remove it. Close upon reaching the level of fill to the west.

Description : Open basket to continue removal of fill in the Northeast Area. The excavation area is irregular in shape, measuring ca. 3.45 m. northwest to southeast and ca. 2.95 m. northeast to southwest. \n\nThe light brown fill is moderately compact with inclusions of bone, metal slag and small chunks of charcoal and plaster. As we take passes, we continue to expose the eastern face of Wall 22. After one pass, we come down to the level of fill immediately to the south, taken in Basket 94, and close due to end of season.
